This paper is about logic programming, specifically linear logic programming, which falls under the category of cs.LO (Logic in Computer Science). The paper also proposes a modification to the operational semantics of linear logic programming, which could be considered a contribution to the field of programming languages and compilers, falling under cs.PL (Programming Languages). The paper also mentions muProlog, an extension of Prolog, which is a popular language in the field of artificial intelligence, falling under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence). The paper also discusses the importance of user interaction in the modified semantics, which could be relevant to the field of software engineering, falling under cs.SE (Software Engineering). Finally, the paper's focus on provability and computation could also be relevant to the field of data structures and algorithms, falling under cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
